\begin{definition}
\label{def:CI}
A \emph{(multiterminal) Wyner common information (${\text{CI}}_W$)} for $X_{\mathcal{M}}$ is a sequence of finite-valued functions $\textsf{L}^{(n)}=\textsf{L}^{(n)}(X_{\mathcal{M}}^n)$ such that $\frac{1}{n}I(X_{\mathcal{M}}^n|\textsf{L}^{(n)}) \to 0$ as $n \to \infty$. An \emph{interactive common information (${\text{CI}}$)} for $X_{\mathcal{M}}$ is a Wyner common information of the form $\textsf{L}^{(n)} = (\textsf{J},\textsf{F})$, where $\textsf{F}$ is an interactive communication and $\textsf{J}$ is a CR obtained from $\textsf{F}$. 
\end{definition}

Similar to Definitions~\ref{def:CR} and \ref{def:SK} we shall drop the superscript $(n)$ from $\textsf{L}^{(n)}$ for notational simplicity. Wyner common informations $\textsf{L}$ do exist: for example, the identity map $\textsf{L}=X_{\mathcal{M}}^n$ is a ${\text{CI}}_W$. To see that ${\text{CI}}$s $(\textsf{J},\textsf{F})$ also exist, observe that $\textsf{J}=X_{\mathcal{M}}^n$ and a communication $\textsf{F}$ enabling omniscience constitute a ${\text{CI}}_W$, and hence, a ${\text{CI}}$.

\begin{definition}
\label{def:CIrate}
