The lemma essentially follows from Lemma~7 in \cite{MNY}. A weighted hypergraph $({\mathcal{M}},{\mathbf{w}})$ is \emph{$t$-uniform} if all hyperedges in ${\mathcal{E}} = \{e \in 2^{{\mathcal{M}}}: {\mathbf{w}}(e) > 0\}$ have size exactly $t$. In particular, a weighted graph satisfies this definition with $t = 2$. We then have the following lemma.

\begin{lemma}[\cite{MNY}, Lemma~7] Let $X_{{\mathcal{M}}}$ be a source defined on a $t$-uniform weighted hypergraph. For any $n \in {\mathbb{N}}$ and any function ${\textsf{L}}$ of $X_{{\mathcal{M}}}^n$, we have

\label{lem:appendix}
\end{lemma}

It should be clarified that Lemma~7 in \cite{MNY} is stated only for hypergraphs with integer-valued weight functions ${\mathbf{w}}$. However, this restriction is not essential for the proof given in \cite{MNY}, so that it applies to any real-valued weight function ${\mathbf{w}}$ just as well. We will need the above lemma only for the case of graphical source models (i.e., $t = 2$).

To prove our Lemma~\ref{lem:mi}, consider the given weighted graph ${\mathcal{G}} = ({\mathcal{M}},{\mathbf{w}})$, with edge set ${\mathcal{E}} = \{e \in 2^{{\mathcal{M}}} : {\mathbf{w}}(e) > 0\}$, and the fundamental partition ${\mathcal{P}}^* = (A_1,\ldots,A_k)$ of the corresponding source $X_{{\mathcal{M}}}$.  From $X_{{\mathcal{M}}}$, we construct a closely related graphical source ${\tilde{X}}_{{\mathcal{V}}}$ on a vertex set ${\mathcal{V}}$, as described next. 

For each pair of cells $A_i,A_j$ of ${\mathcal{P}}^*$, with $i < j$, let ${\mathcal{E}}_{i,j}$ denote the set of edges of ${\mathcal{G}}$ with one endpoint in $A_i$ and the other in $A_j$. We further let ${\mathcal{E}}_i$ be the set of edges of ${\mathcal{G}}$ that are contained within $A_i$, $i = 1,2,\ldots,k$. Now, let $\{a_1,\ldots,a_k\}$ and $\{a_1',\ldots,a_k'\}$ be two disjoint sets of size $k = {|{\mathcal{P}}^*|}$ each, and let ${\mathcal{V}} = \{a_1,\ldots,a_k\} \cup \{a_1',\ldots,a_k'\}$. Define a weight function ${\tilde{{\mathbf{w}}}}$ on $2$-subsets of ${\mathcal{V}}$ as follows: for each pair of integers $i < j$, we set ${\tilde{{\mathbf{w}}}}(\{a_i,a_j\}) = \sum_{e \in {\mathcal{E}}_{i,j}} {\mathbf{w}}(e)$; and for $i = 1,2,\ldots,k$, set ${\tilde{{\mathbf{w}}}}(\{a_i,a_i'\}) = \sum_{e \in A_i} {\tilde{{\mathbf{w}}}}(e)$. For all other $2$-subsets $\tilde{e}$ of ${\mathcal{V}}$, we set ${\tilde{{\mathbf{w}}}}(\tilde{e}) = 0$.

We take ${{\tilde{X}}}_{{\mathcal{V}}}$ to be a source defined on the weighted graph $({\mathcal{V}},{\tilde{{\mathbf{w}}}})$. To be precise, let $\xi_e$, $e \in {\mathcal{E}}$, be the random variables associated with the edges of the graphical source $X_{{\mathcal{M}}}$. In ${\tilde{X}}_{{\mathcal{V}}}$, we associate with each $2$-subset (edge) $\tilde{e}$ of ${\mathcal{V}}$, a random variable $\tilde{\xi}_{\tilde{e}}$ as below:

